<section xml:id="section-graphing-equations">
  <title>Graphing Equations</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-create-table-of-values" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-label-and-scale-axes" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-different-scales" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-identify-linear-equation-in-two-variables" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-emphasize-graph-solution-set" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-plot-linear-equation-from-three-solutions" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>
    We have graphed <em>points</em> in a coordinate system, and now we will graph <em>lines</em>
    and <em>curves</em>.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
    <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-cYCLcYMtd7GdwFZ4DRDTBc" />
  </figure>

  <p>
    A <term>graph</term> of an equation is a picture of that equation's solution set. For example,            <idx><h>Graph</h><h>of an equation</h></idx>
    the graph of <m>y=-2x+3</m> is shown in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full"/>. The                         <idx><h>Equations in two variables</h><h>graphing</h></idx>
    graph plots ordered pairs whose coordinates make <m>y=-2x+3</m> true.                                     <idx><h>Graphing</h><h>equations in two variables</h></idx>
    <xref ref="table-check-points-for-line"/> shows a few points that make the equation                       <idx><h>Ordered pair</h><h>as solution of equation</h></idx>
    true.                                                                                                     <idx><h>Plotting points</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Points</h><h>plotting</h></idx>
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="38% 59%" margins="0%">
    <table xml:id="table-check-points-for-line">
      <title />
      <tabular>
        <col halign="center" />
        <col halign="center" />
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell><m>(x,y)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>y=-2x+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{-1},\substitute{5})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{5}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{-1})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{0},\substitute{3})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{3}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{0})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{1},\substitute{1})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{1}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{1})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{2},\substitute{-1})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{-1}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{2})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{3},\substitute{-3})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{-3}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{3})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>(\substitute{4},\substitute{-5})</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\substitute{-5}\confirm{=}-2(\substitute{4})+3</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <p>
      <xref ref="table-check-points-for-line"/> tells us that the points <m>(-1,5)</m>,
      <m>(0,3)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m>, <m>(2,-1)</m>, <m>(3,-3)</m>, and <m>(4,-5)</m> are all solutions           <idx><h>Solution(s)</h><h>of equations in two variables</h></idx>
      to the equation <m>y=-2x+3</m>, and so they should all be shaded as part of that equation's
      graph. You can see them in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-sparse">Figure</xref>. But there are
      many more points that make the equation true. More points are plotted in
      <xref ref="figure-graph-line-more"/>. Even more points are plotted in
      <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full"/><mdash/>so many, that together the points look like a
      straight line.
    </p>
  </sidebyside>

  <figure>
    <caption>Graphs of the Equation <m>y=-2x+3</m></caption>
    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
      <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-sparse">
        <caption>A few points<ellipsis/></caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a Cartesian graph of the points listed in the text that are solutions to the equation
            y=-2x+3;
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="points-on-yequals-2x+3">
            {
              \footnotesize
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,5)} node[rotate=30,left]{$(-1,5)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,3)}  node[rotate=30,right]{$(0,3)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)}  node[rotate=30,right]{$(1,1)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(2,-1)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,-3)} node[rotate=30,left]{$(3,-3)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-5)} node[rotate=30,left]{$(4,-5)$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            }
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-more">
        <caption>More points<ellipsis /></caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a second Cartesian graph showing all of the points listed in the first graph and
            additional solutions to y=-2x+3 between those points
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="more-points-on-yequals-2x+3">
            {
              \footnotesize
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1.5,6) (-1.2,5.4) (-1,5) (-0.8,4.6) (-0.3, 3.6)
                    (0,3) (0.4,2.2) (1,1) (1.1,0.8) (1.7,-0.4) (2,-1) (2.3,-1.6) (2.6,-2.2) (3,-3)
                    (3.5,-4) (4,-5) (4.3,-5.6) (4.8,-6.6)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            }
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-full">
        <caption>So many points it looks like a straight line</caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a third Cartesian graph showing so many points that are solutions of the line y=-2x+3
            that they overlap and form a solid line
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="line-for-yequals-2x+3">
            {
              \footnotesize
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {-2*x+3};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            }
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The graph of an equation shades all the points <m>(x,y)</m> that make the equation true once the
    <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values are substituted in. Typically, there are so many points shaded,
    that the final graph appears to be a continuous line or curve that you could draw with one
    stroke of a pen.
  </p>

  <exercise label="check-point-in-equation">
    <webwork>
      <pg-macros>
        <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
      </pg-macros>
      <pg-code>
        Context()->variables->add(y => 'Real');
        $y = -5;
        $f = Compute("-2(4) + 3");
        $truefalse = DropDown(['The equation is true.','The equation is fase.'], 0, showInStatic => 0);
      </pg-code>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The point <m>(4,-5)</m> is on the graph in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full"/>. What
          happens when you substitute these values into the equation <m>y=-2x+3</m>?
        </p>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="right" />
          <col halign="center" />
          <col halign="left" />
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-2x+3</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><var name="$y" width="2" /></cell>
            <cell><m>\wonder{=}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-2(</m><var name="4" width="2"/><m>)+3</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><var name="$y" width="2" /></cell>
            <cell><m>\wonder{=}</m></cell>
            <cell><var name="$f" width="10" /></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
          <var name="$truefalse" form="popup" />
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Each side of the equation simplifies to <m>-5</m>. In other words, the equation simplifies
          to an outright true equation.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>
  <exercise label="check-points-in-equation">
    <webwork>
      <pg-macros>
        <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
      </pg-macros>
      <pg-code>
        Context()->variables->add(y => 'Real');
        @y = (-2,-7);
        @x = (5,-10);
        Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants => 0);
        $f = Compute("-(3/5)x + 1");
        @right = map{$f->substitute(x => Formula($x[$_]))}(0,1);
        @d = (
          DropDown(['It is included in the graph.','It is not included in the graph.'], 0, showInStatic => 0),
          DropDown(['It is included in the graph.','It is not included in the graph.'], 1, showInStatic => 0),
        );
      </pg-code>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Decide whether <m>(5,-2)</m> and <m>(-10,-7)</m> are on the graph of the equation
          <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m>.
        </p>
        <instruction>
          At <m>(5,-2)</m>:
        </instruction>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="right" />
          <col halign="center" />
          <col halign="left" />
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><var name="$y[0]" width="2" /></cell>
            <cell><m>\wonder{=}</m></cell>
            <cell><var name="$right[0]" width="10" /></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
          <var name="$d[0]" form="popup" />
        </p>
        <instruction>
          At <m>(-10,-7)</m>:
        </instruction>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="right" />
          <col halign="center" />
          <col halign="left" />
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><var name="$y[1]" width="2" /></cell>
            <cell><m>\wonder{=}</m></cell>
            <cell><var name="$right[1]" width="10" /></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
          <var name="$d[0]" form="popup" />
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If the point <m>(5,-2)</m> is on <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m>, once we substitute <m>x=5</m>
          and <m>y=-2</m> into the line's equation, the equation should be true. Let's try:
          <md>
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</mrow>
            <mrow>-2\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{3}{5}(5)+1</mrow>
            <mrow>-2\amp\confirm{=} -3+1</mrow>
          </md>
          Because this last equation is true, we can say that <m>(5,-2)</m> is on the graph of
          <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          However if we substitute <m>x=-10</m> and <m>y=-7</m> into the equation, it leads to
          <m>-7=7</m>, which is false. This tells us that <m>(-10,-7)</m> is <em>not</em> on the
          graph.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    To make our own graph of an equation with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we can choose
    some reasonable <m>x</m>-values, then calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot
    the <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs as points. For many algebraic equations, connecting those points with a
    smooth curve will produce an excellent graph.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="example-plot-using-table">
    <p>
      Let's plot a graph for the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>. We use a table to organize our work:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Set up the table</caption>
          <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
              <cell>Point</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{-2(\substitute{-2})+5=\highlight{9}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{-2(\substitute{-1})+5=\highlight{7}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{-2(\substitute{0})+5=\highlight{5}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{-2(\substitute{1})+5=\highlight{3}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="none">
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{-2(\substitute{2})+5=\highlight{1}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <caption>Complete the table</caption>
          <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
              <cell>Point</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2(\substitute{-2})+5=\highlight{9}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2(\substitute{-1})+5=\highlight{7}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2(\substitute{0})+5=\highlight{5}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2(\substitute{1})+5=\highlight{3}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="none">
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2(\substitute{2})+5=\highlight{1}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

    <p>
      We use points from the table to graph the equation in <xref ref="figure-graphing-a-line"/>.
      First, we need a coordinate system to draw onto. We will eventually need to see the
      <m>x</m>-values <m>-2</m>, <m>-1</m>, <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, and <m>2</m> on the graph. So drawing
      an <m>x</m>-axis that runs from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m> will be good enough. We will eventually
      need to see the <m>y</m>-values <m>9</m>, <m>7</m>, <m>5</m>, <m>3</m>, and <m>1</m> too. So
      drawing a <m>y</m>-axis that runs from <m>-1</m> to <m>10</m> will be good enough.
    </p>
    <p>
      Axes should always be labeled using the variable names they represent. In this case, with
      <q><m>x</m></q> and <q><m>y</m></q>. The axes should have tick marks that are spaced evenly.
      In this case it is fine to place the tick marks one unit apart (on both axes). Labeling at
      least some of the tick marks is necessary for a reader to understand the scale. Here we label
      the even-numbered ticks.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then connect the points with a smooth curve. Here, the curve is a straight line. Lastly, we
      can communicate that the graph extends further by sketching arrows on both ends of the line.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-graphing-a-line">
      <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
      <sbsgroup>
        <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            Decisions we made about the scale for each axis is drawn in <xref ref="figure-graphing-a-line-a"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next we carefully plot each point from the table in <xref ref="figure-graphing-a-line-b"/>.
            It's not necessary to label each point's coordinates, but we do so here.
          </p>
          <p>
            Last we connect the points with a smooth curve. Here, the <q>curve</q> is a straight
            line. We communicate that the line extends further by putting arrowheads on both ends.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
        <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
          <figure xml:id="figure-graphing-a-line-a">
            <caption>Staging the coordinate system</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>a blank Cartesian grid</shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="empty-grid">
                {
                  \footnotesize
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                        ymin=-1,
                        ymax=10,
                        xtick={-6,-4,...,6},
                        minor xtick={-6,-5,...,6},
                        ytick={2,4,...,8},
                        minor ytick={1,2,...,9}
                      ]
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="figure-graphing-a-line-b">
            <caption>Points from the table</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>
                a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)
              </shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="points-from-the-table">
                {
                  \footnotesize
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                        ymin=-1,
                        ymax=10,
                        xtick={-6,-4,...,6},
                        minor xtick={-6,-5,...,6},
                        ytick={2,4,...,8},
                        minor ytick={1,2,...,9}
                      ]
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)}  node[right,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)}  node[right,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)}  node[right,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="figure-graphing-a-line-c">
            <caption>Extend the pattern that is apparent</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>
                a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1) connected with a solid line
              </shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="interpolated-and-extrapolated-line">
                {
                  \footnotesize
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                        ymin=-1,
                        ymax=10,
                        xtick={-6,-4,...,6},
                        minor xtick={-6,-5,...,6},
                        ytick={2,4,...,8},
                        minor ytick={1,2,...,9}
                      ]
                      \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </sbsgroup>
    </figure>
  </example>

  <p>
    Note that our choice of <m>x</m>-values in the table was arbitrary. As long as we determine the
    coordinates of enough points to indicate the behavior of the graph, we may choose whichever
    <m>x</m>-values we like. Having a few negative <m>x</m>-values will be good. For simpler
    calculations, it's fine to choose <m>-2</m>, <m>-1</m>, <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, and <m>2</m>.
  </p>

  <exercise label="plot-an-equation-with-fraction">
    <webwork>
      <pg-macros>
        <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
      </pg-macros>
      <pg-code>
        Context("Point");
        $gt = GraphTool(
          "{point,(-6,-12)}",
          "{point,(-3,-8)}",
          "{point,(0,-4)}",
          "{point,(3,0)}",
          "{point,(6,4)}",
          "{line,solid,(-6,-12),(-3,-8)}"
        )->with(
          bBox => [-7, 5, 7, -15],
          availableTools => [ "PointTool", "LineTool" ],
          showCoordinateHints => 0,
          showInStatic => 0,
        );
