  <p>
    Sometimes an equation has context that suggests using other <m>x</m>-values, as in the next
    example.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="example-gas-mileage">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The gas tank in Sofia's car holds
        <quantity>
          <mag>14</mag><unit base="gallon" />
        </quantity>
        of fuel. Over the course of a long road trip, her car uses fuel at an average rate of
        <quantity>
          <mag>0.032</mag><unit base="gallon"/><per base="mile"/>
        </quantity>.
        If Sofia fills the tank at the beginning of a long trip, then the amount of fuel remaining
        in the tank, <m>y</m>, after driving <m>x</m> miles is given by the equation
        <m>y=14-0.032x</m>. Make a suitable table of values and graph this equation.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Choosing <m>x</m>-values from <m>-2</m> to <m>2</m> as in an earlier example wouldn't make
        sense here. Sofia cannot drive a negative number of miles, and any long road trip is longer
        than <m>2</m> miles. So in this context, choose <m>x</m>-values that reflect the number of
        miles Sofia might possibly drive in a day. We choose values like <m>20</m> and <m>200</m>,
        as well as several values in between.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Make the table</caption>
          <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m> (miles)</cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>y=14-0.032x</m></cell>
              <cell>Point</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>20</m></cell>
              <cell><m>13.36</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(20,13.36)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>50</m></cell>
              <cell><m>12.4</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(50,12.4)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>80</m></cell>
              <cell><m>11.44</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(80,11.44)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>100</m></cell>
              <cell><m>10.8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(100,10.8)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="none">
              <cell><m>200</m></cell>
              <cell><m>7.6</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(200,7.6)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-sofias-road-trip">
          <caption>Make the graph</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              a Cartesian graph of the points listed in the table; the points are connected by a
              solid line with an arrow to the right
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="graph-of-points-for-yequals14-0.032x">
              {
                \footnotesize
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \begin{axis}[
                      xmin=0,
                      xmax=250,
                      ymin=0,
                      ymax=20,
                      xlabel={$x$ (miles)},
                      ylabel={$y$ (gallons)},
                      xtick=,
                      minor xtick={0,10,...,250},
                      ytick=,
                      minor ytick={0,1,...,20},
                      clip=false,
                      grid=major,
                      axis line style={->},
                      width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    ]
                    \addplot+[domain=0:250,->] {14-0.032*x};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(20,13.36)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(20,13.36)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(50,12.4)}  node[above right,rotate=30]{$(50,12.4)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(80,11.44)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(80,11.44)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(100,10.8)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(100,10.8)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(200,7.6)}  node[above right,rotate=30]{$(200,7.6)$};
                  \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
              }
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="figure-sofias-road-trip"/>, notice how both axes are also labeled with
        <em>units</em> (<q>gallons</q> and <q>miles</q>). When the equation you plot has context like
        this example, including the units in the axes labels is very important to help anyone who
        reads your graph to understand it better.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the table, <m>x</m>-values ran from <m>20</m> to <m>200</m>, while <m>y</m>-values ran
        from <m>13.36</m> down to <m>7.6</m>. So it was appropriate to make the <m>x</m>-axis cover
        something like from <m>0</m> to <m>250</m>, and make the <m>y</m>-axis cover something like
        from <m>0</m> to <m>20</m>. The scales on the two axes ended up being different.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
