  <p>
    In this last example, the points did not fall on a straight line. Many algebraic equations have
    graphs that are non-linear, where the points do not fall on a straight line. What is it that
    makes an equation <em>have</em> a straight line?
  </p>

  <p>
    A <term>linear expression</term> in two variables is an expression in the form <m>ax+by+c</m>,
    where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are numbers, at least one of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> is
    nonzero, and <m>x</m>, <m>y</m> are variables. For example, <m>2x+3y+1</m> and
    <m>x-3y+\frac{1}{2}</m> are linear expressions in two variables. We also count an expression
    like <m>x+1</m> as a linear expression in two variables, if we view it as <m>x+0y+1</m>.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-linear-equation-in-two-variables">
    <title>Linear Equation in Two Variables</title>                                                           <idx><h>Equations in two variables</h><h>linear</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Linear equations in two variables</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>linear equation</term> in two variables is any equation where you could add/subtract
        terms in such a way as to get a linear expression in two variables on one side, and <m>0</m>
        on the other side.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    The following are each an example of a linear equation in two variables. Note that if you only
    see one variable in one of these equations, you can add the other variable somewhere with
    coefficient <m>0</m>.
    <md>
      <mrow>x-y\amp=5 \amp 4x+y\amp=5x \amp 10\amp=\frac{1}{2}x</mrow>
    </md>
    <md>
      <mrow>3-2(p+2)\amp=5q \amp \sqrt{2} r+t\amp=10 \amp s+2t\amp=\frac{s}{2}+3</mrow>
    </md>
    Note that <m>r</m> is outside the square root symbol.
  </p>

  <p>
    A linear equation in two variables never does things like square a variable, or take the
    square root of a variable. It never has a variable in a denominator. It never multiplies the two
    variables together. Etc. It can only multiply a variable by constant, and then add to other
    terms to form one side or the other of the equation.
  </p>

  <p>
    The following are not linear equations in two variables:
    <dl>
      <li>
        <title><m>1+2=3</m></title>
        <p>
          There is no variable.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title><m>4x^2-2y^2=5</m></title>
        <p>
          The variables are squared
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title><m>\sqrt{2r}+3t=10</m></title>
        <p>
          The variable <m>r</m> is inside the square root.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title><m>5s-t=\frac{2}{s}+3</m></title>
        <p>
          The variable <m>s</m> is in a denominator.
        </p>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </p>

  <p>
    If you learn to recognize when a given equation in two variables is linear, then you will know
    ahead of time that its graph is some sort of straight line.
  </p>

